{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652906"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:41:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:41:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18544"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18544"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11276"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76182"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11276"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18544"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61685"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"10900"},{"type":"tags","id":"10905"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26147"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26153"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26183"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76182"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe tapeworm \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus granulosus\u003C/em\u003E requires specific hosts to complete its lifecycle. Adult worms live in the intestines of dogs (definitive host) and release eggs that are ingested by sheep (intermediate host), where they form hydatid cysts in various organs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the role of sheep as intermediate hosts in the Echinococcus lifecycle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Support development of larval cysts into infective forms","Transport eggs between different dog populations","Provide nutrition for adult tapeworms","Protect eggs from environmental damage","Serve as permanent habitat for mature worms"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESheep as intermediate hosts \u003Cstrong\u003Esupport development of larval cysts into infective forms\u003C/strong\u003E. When sheep ingest \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus\u003C/em\u003E eggs, these develop into hydatid cysts containing protoscolices, which can develop into adult tapeworms when dogs consume infected sheep organs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport eggs between different dog populations\u003C/strong\u003E - Sheep do not transport eggs; they are infected by consuming eggs from contaminated pasture\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide nutrition for adult tapeworms\u003C/strong\u003E - Adult tapeworms live and feed exclusively in the dog intestine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtect eggs from environmental damage\u003C/strong\u003E - Eggs are released into the environment by dogs, not protected by sheep\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EServe as permanent habitat for mature worms\u003C/strong\u003E - Mature tapeworms only live in dogs (definitive host), while sheep host the larval hydatid cyst stage\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe intermediate host role of sheep is crucial as it allows the development of infective larval forms (protoscolices within hydatid cysts) that can then mature into adult tapeworms when ingested by dogs. Man can become an intermediate host by the inadvertent ingestion of \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus\u003C/em\u003E eggs. The subsequent hatching of the egg in the intestine is followed by the development of the oncosphere which penetrates the intestinal wall, enters the vascular system and becomes deposited in a organ (typically liver and spleen), where the hydatid cyst forms. These parasitic infections used to be seen regularly in the sheep-rearing areas of Australia, but since the de-worming of dogs and better hygiene hydatid disease is now uncommon. It is seen occasionally as an incidental finding on imaging and mainly in individuals who have come from a part of the world where the disease is still prevalent (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Echinococcus requires both definitive hosts (dogs) and intermediate hosts (sheep) to complete its lifecycle.","Adult Echinococcus tapeworms live in dog intestines and release eggs that are ingested by sheep.","Hydatid cysts develop in sheep organs and contain protoscolices that become adult worms when dogs eat infected meat."],"references":["Eckert J, Deplazes P. Biological, epidemiological, and clinical aspects of echinococcosis, a zoonosis of increasing concern. Clin Microbiol Rev. 2004 Jan;17(1):107-35. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC321468/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61685"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18544"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21409"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21409"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/g31ocDmVHNOreDO3ZYwUvxCdU3RWTs.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/g31ocDmVHNOreDO3ZYwUvxCdU3RWTs.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":497,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61685"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T09:36:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T09:36:40+10:30"},